the book is saying because I feel like we
need a little bit of that right now.

00:44:40.400 --> 00:44:43.200
It's not
as though you set up a decentralized network

00:44:43.200 --> 00:44:46.880
and let everybody participate and you're golden,
right?

00:44:46.880 --> 00:44:52.850
I mean what happens when you
create much more diverse unplanned networks

00:44:52.850 --> 00:44:58.500
is it introduces, by definition, it introduces
more noise and chaos into the system.

00:44:58.500 --> 00:45:01.410
The
beautiful thing about perfectly planned environments

00:45:01.410 --> 00:45:02.860
is they're very controlled.

00:45:02.860 --> 00:45:05.990
They may be nightmares, but they don't have
that

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:11.200
kind of ragged noisiness and when you open
up a platform to anybody that means it is

00:45:11.200 --> 00:45:18.280
filled with all sorts of cranks, and people
with an agenda, and scam artists, and people

00:45:18.280 --> 00:45:21.420
who are trying to abuse the system in one
way or another, or people who are just wrong

00:45:21.420 --> 00:45:25.750
and misguided in their views [laughter] and
trying to steer with good intentions in the

00:45:25.750 --> 00:45:28.040
wrong way, right?

00:45:28.040 --> 00:45:33.460
So to that I think you have to take that seriously
and that means you have to design the architecture

00:45:33.460 --> 00:45:37.960
of these things so they
subdue that as much as possible.

00:45:37.960 --> 00:45:41.350
And this is exactly what Kickstarter is trying
to do right now.

00:45:41.350 --> 00:45:44.040
They're an experiment and they're
constantly going to be tweaking things just

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:50.060
as Google has been tweaking page rank to deal
with people trying to exploit it from

00:45:50.060 --> 00:45:52.000
almost day one.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:57.880
It's an inevitable part of the process.

00:45:57.880 --> 00:46:02.130
The two things I've been saying to people
when this comes up are:

00:46:02.130 --> 00:46:06.150
One, these are also the objections people
make about democracies, right?

00:46:06.150 --> 00:46:10.430
We've decided, in general, most of us around
the world,

00:46:10.430 --> 00:46:15.880
that despite the fact that democracies open
up the voting process to cranks and scam artists

00:46:15.880 --> 00:46:18.410
and people who are just wrong.

00:46:18.410 --> 00:46:20.090
That in
the long run they're better than these other

00:46:20.090 --> 00:46:24.820
systems because they involve a much more diverse
make up of decision makers that

00:46:24.820 --> 00:46:27.020
better represent the needs of the overall
population.

00:46:27.020 --> 00:46:31.590
And so it doesn't mean that democracies work
the second you set them up and

00:46:31.590 --> 00:46:33.870
you have to be constantly tinkering with them.

00:46:33.870 --> 00:46:36.390
The other example, I think, is Wikipedia,
right?

00:46:36.390 --> 00:46:43.330
This is one of the places where the media
has been--you know I think they've skewed

00:46:43.330 --> 00:46:47.990
things by focusing disproportionally on the
places where Wikipedia fails.

00:46:47.990 --> 00:46:52.620
In the book I say it's a bit like aviation
history right?

00:46:52.620 --> 00:46:59.130
The news with the aviation should be the astonishingly
large number, high percentage of flights that

00:46:59.130 --> 00:47:03.760
you know take off and land
with perfect safety, rather than the plane

00:47:03.760 --> 00:47:04.760
crash.

00:47:04.760 --> 00:47:07.940
But, of course, we cover the plane crash;
same thing with Wikipedia.

00:47:07.940 --> 00:47:10.380
Incredible
news every day should be this thing works

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:12.200
99.9 percent of the time.

00:47:12.200 --> 00:47:15.731
[laughs] It's amazing that it works, and yes
every now and then, there

00:47:15.731 --> 00:47:21.110
are articles where someone has abused that
platform, said something libelous, said something

00:47:21.110 --> 00:47:28.140
insane, but, they've, overtime, built this
ind of social architecture that encourages

00:47:28.140 --> 00:47:31.420
more truth and less falsehoods.

00:47:31.420 --> 00:47:36.430
[chuckles] And it, the system kind of trends
toward more

00:47:36.430 --> 00:47:41.910
accuracy despite it having any traditional
top down experts deciding things.

00:47:41.910 --> 00:47:46.740
So each problem, each network is gonna be
unique.

00:47:46.740 --> 00:47:51.210
The problem of a neighborhood self-organizing
and creating a peer network to solve its needs

00:47:51.210 --> 00:47:58.240
is probably going to be different from a global
encyclopedia, but I think there are probably

00:47:58.240 --> 00:48:02.690
some common threads that we can
learn, best practices that we can apply that

00:48:02.690 --> 00:48:04.350
deal with those problems.

00:48:04.350 --> 00:48:07.980
But it does involve a certain lack of control
and a certain

00:48:07.980 --> 00:48:13.600
increase in noise and unpredictability to
the system for sure.

00:48:13.600 --> 00:48:18.360
But I think we've gotten smart enough to figure
out ways around some of those

00:48:18.360 --> 00:48:19.360
problems.

00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:20.360
Yes?

00:48:20.360 --> 00:48:24.220
&gt;&gt;Male #2: It's interesting when you talk
about peer based networks and there's a difference

00:48:24.220 --> 00:48:27.920
between the way Kickstarter
works and the way Wikipedia works.

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:32.860
And that's to me in the term of authorship,
ownership and credit, so recognition that

00:48:32.860 --> 00:48:34.560
I did this
project.

00:48:34.560 --> 00:48:36.820
Wikipedia doesn't seem to have that.

00:48:36.820 --> 00:48:41.190
You don't take pride in saying, 'I edited
that', it's just for you to enjoy.

00:48:41.190 --> 00:48:43.570
And similar
behavior comes in when you think about Internet

00:48:43.570 --> 00:48:44.570
memes.

00:48:44.570 --> 00:48:47.940
So I made an Internet meme of a hipster kitty,
I laugh at it.

00:48:47.940 --> 00:48:50.790
I don't expect
the world to know that I made it.

00:48:50.790 --> 00:48:53.580
But that's not the model with Kickstarter
where there's abs--.

00:48:53.580 --> 00:48:57.070
There's two kinds of recognition, there's
one of the artist or the maker who

00:48:57.070 --> 00:48:59.220
says, "I made this project, give me the money.

00:48:59.220 --> 00:49:01.340
If I get the money, I'm going to make it."

00:49:01.340 --> 00:49:06.260
Then you go and there's this social
cachet that you get, "I backed this gaming

00:49:06.260 --> 00:49:08.080
console and so I'm great."

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:12.110
So what to you think is the balance of that
and where do

00:49:12.110 --> 00:49:14.580
you see that heading, especially when it comes
to governments and things like that?

00:49:14.580 --> 00:49:19.490
&gt;&gt;Steve Johnson: Yeah, that's a really good
important observation which I didn't fully

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:21.740
address in the book.

00:49:21.740 --> 00:49:25.911
You know, the common
theme to that is this idea again which again

00:49:25.911 --> 00:49:33.660
is not news since inside of Google is that
people will be motivated by a much wider

00:49:33.660 --> 00:49:38.430
range of rewards than traditional economics
believes.

00:49:38.430 --> 00:49:41.750
You know, Dan Pink has written about this
a little bit in Drive.

00:49:41.750 --> 00:49:43.740
And
sometimes when you offer money you get less

00:49:43.740 --> 00:49:44.740
motivation.

00:49:44.740 --> 00:49:46.540
People are like, "No, I want esteem.

00:49:46.540 --> 00:49:51.910
I want the recognition of my peers,"
for instance, to use the word peer again can

00:49:51.910 --> 00:49:53.860
be a big driver.

00:49:53.860 --> 00:50:04.800
So what all these systems have showed us in
real, vivid, practical success stories is

00:50:04.800 --> 00:50:11.500
that the tools that are available, the
rewards that are available to incentivize

00:50:11.500 --> 00:50:12.620
people to participate are--.

00:50:12.620 --> 00:50:16.310
There's a much wider range.

00:50:16.310 --> 00:50:22.840
Everything from "we'll give you
two dollars" to "you will silently know that

00:50:22.840 --> 00:50:27.970
you made this entry on Wikipedia about the
Challenger explosion slightly better by

00:50:27.970 --> 00:50:29.610
fixing that one sentence."

00:50:29.610 --> 00:50:32.540
[ chuckles] And you'll have that personal
sense of it.

00:50:32.540 --> 00:50:39.800
I, to me, I think, the amazing thing about
Wikipedia is that it works as well as it does

00:50:39.800 --> 00:50:43.450
with so little recognition.

00:50:43.450 --> 00:50:46.220
You know, I
think probably with Kickstarter, they wanted

00:50:46.220 --> 00:50:52.120
to--and it may partially be because Kickstarter
is a site that started post-Facebook

00:50:52.120 --> 00:50:58.270
and Twitter, where Wikipedia predates all
of that, so they went into it assuming that

00:50:58.270 --> 00:51:03.960
all your activities would be amplified and
shared in some kind of public way and you

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:08.690
could use that “Hey, I just backed this
project on Kickstarter, aren't I awesome?"

00:51:08.690 --> 00:51:10.370
to
incentivize people to back more projects on

00:51:10.370 --> 00:51:12.990
Kickstarter.

00:51:12.990 --> 00:51:15.560
And it would be very interesting to see what
would have happened--.

00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:19.030
It's kind of a cool thought experiment, it's
not really run

00:51:19.030 --> 00:51:21.761
through in my head so I don't have the answer,
what Wikipedia would have looked like had

00:51:21.761 --> 00:51:25.310
it been created post Facebook and Twitter.

00:51:25.310 --> 00:51:32.220
So, it does kind of amaze me that Wikipedia
gets as much participation as it does given

00:51:32.220 --> 00:51:35.910
that the reward is so genuinely slight.

00:51:35.910 --> 00:51:38.680
Any others?

00:51:38.680 --> 00:51:49.050
&gt;&gt;Male #3: So, in this peer based model, where
do you see experts?

00:51:49.050 --> 00:51:50.050
What's their role?

00:51:50.050 --> 00:51:51.090
Is it different?

00:51:51.090 --> 00:51:54.811
Or is it, well, I'll
let you answer.

00:51:54.811 --> 00:51:55.811
&gt;&gt;Steve Johnson: Yeah.

00:51:55.811 --> 00:51:57.820
I think there is a role for experts.

00:51:57.820 --> 00:52:03.510
Look, you know, I want to be disingenuous
about this.

00:52:03.510 --> 00:52:07.820
I didn't crowd
source the book, I wrote it as an individual

00:52:07.820 --> 00:52:09.020
author.

00:52:09.020 --> 00:52:14.610
And it is a book that is very much connective
and it's drawing upon ideas and

00:52:14.610 --> 00:52:20.320
projects that have inspired me and part of
what I do is just relay that news in the book.

00:52:20.320 --> 00:52:25.320
But I still feel that books happen to be
a form that generally work better if there

00:52:25.320 --> 00:52:29.500
is one author than other forms.

00:52:29.500 --> 00:52:34.220
So there are cases where individuals with
a certain

00:52:34.220 --> 00:52:39.820
message, particularly a structure of an argument
or storytelling form generally --for complicated

00:52:39.820 --> 00:52:42.240
reasons that I don't totally have
an answer for-- generally have worked better

00:52:42.240 --> 00:52:44.890
with one person doing it than with a crowd
doing it.

00:52:44.890 --> 00:52:46.870
So it's not that the crowd can
solve everything.

00:52:46.870 --> 00:52:50.770
And in terms of experts, what I think has
started happening, and I think this is one

00:52:50.770 --> 00:52:57.021
of the things been an enduring success of
what we used to

00:52:57.021 --> 00:53:09.370
call the "blogosphere" [laughs] is actually
again extending the realm of expertise.

00:53:09.370 --> 00:53:13.200
You know I notice this a lot in the financial
crises.

00:53:13.200 --> 00:53:18.040
And I wrote about this a little bit in the
book, leading up the election in 2008.

00:53:18.040 --> 00:53:24.030
That one of the things that was there
then that wasn't there for instance when there

00:53:24.030 --> 00:53:27.960
was the recession before Clinton was elected,
and there was a lot of talk about

00:53:27.960 --> 00:53:31.720
politics and how either party were going to
fix the economy.

00:53:31.720 --> 00:53:35.370
You had a certain number of experts that would
show up on the pages of the Wall Street Journal,

00:53:35.370 --> 00:53:39.650
or the pages of The New York Times, the Op
Ed pages and you had a political class of

00:53:39.650 --> 00:53:44.470
pundits who would talk about these issues
on CNN or something like that.

00:53:44.470 --> 00:53:48.710
But by 2008, you had
this amazing new caste in the middle there

00:53:48.710 --> 00:53:54.560
of academics actually, economists who were
working at schools who were actually trained

00:53:54.560 --> 00:53:59.660
in the field who were not necessarily pundits,
who were not going to go on these shows, but

00:53:59.660 --> 00:54:03.260
had an extraordinary amount of
expertise, actually more expertise than most

00:54:03.260 --> 00:54:05.470
of the people who'd been on television before.

00:54:05.470 --> 00:54:12.610
Who now, thanks to blogging, were able
to kind of weigh in on all these topics and

00:54:12.610 --> 00:54:16.180
give us both some guidance and interpretation
from that kind of point of view without

00:54:16.180 --> 00:54:20.740
having to fight their way onto the Op Ed page
of The New York Times.

00:54:20.740 --> 00:54:25.700
And it's not that the experts were gone, it
wasn't that we

00:54:25.700 --> 00:54:32.270
were like, “Okay, crowd, decide whether
the Bush, I mean , McCain plan or the Obama

00:54:32.270 --> 00:54:33.980
plan is better for getting out of this mess
or

00:54:33.980 --> 00:54:35.950
explain why Lehman Brothers collapsed."

00:54:35.950 --> 00:54:38.130
The crowd is not going to answer that.

00:54:38.130 --> 00:54:46.230
But what we have now is a much wider pool
of those informed experts to draw upon and

00:54:46.230 --> 00:54:52.900
that's what, and again, that's a place where,
you know, blogging seems so passé now.

00:54:52.900 --> 00:54:58.470
But you go to a good blogger who's a great
curator of interesting links to things and

00:54:58.470 --> 00:55:00.980
you
can sit down with them and see something they've

00:55:00.980 --> 00:55:04.900
put together of all these econo-bloggers who
are out there writing about these

00:55:04.900 --> 00:55:06.220
issues.

00:55:06.220 --> 00:55:11.280
That's an incredible resource that we just
did not have ten or fifteen years ago, and

00:55:11.280 --> 00:55:16.060
it's in part because it's amplifying
the voices of experts but it's created a much

00:55:16.060 --> 00:55:18.340
bigger pool of experts.

00:55:18.340 --> 00:55:21.510
All right.

00:55:21.510 --> 00:55:26.570
Thank you so much for visiting and I'm happy
to sign books and I really appreciate you

00:55:26.570 --> 00:55:27.570
guys coming out.

00:55:27.570 --> 00:55:28.570
Appreciate it.

00:55:28.570 --> 00:55:28.571
[Applause]

